Local_Seafood_Text: Landing fish in NC that is caught in RI (summer flounder) is neither local nor fresh
Benefit_Local: I rarely buy local seafood because of the destructive fishing practices the State of NC allows in its waters.  Oyster dredging, shrimp trawling, gill nets and blue crabs (lost posts, throwing cardboard boxes from bait overboard).  I catch/harvest my own mostly  or buy out of state, such as salmon.
Fresh, tasty
Local support

Net negative. NC seafood is some of the most unsustainable in the country. We’re better off eating seafood from Maine or Alaska. At least that’s sustainable. The most sustainable fish in carteret county is a filet of fish sandwich from McDonald’s. At least it’s not from a local seafood market that lies to me about its origin, the gear that caught it and it’s sustainability.

Supports local businesses and providers in lieu of larger commercial enterprises, ensures freshness, and reinforces local relationships within community.

My family loves seafood and we know that by buying local (Carteret Catch or NC Catch) we are also supporting our local commercial fishermen.  Although our local seafood market also stocks fish from out of state (farmed salmon for example) it is of higher quality and taste than frozen salmon from local grocery stores.  I very much support mariculture especially the delicious oysters that are being raised in Carteret County and soft shell crabs. We truly believe our steady diet of mostly seafood, very little red meat is a healthy choice and one we are willing to pay extra for high, quality local shrimp, grouper and triggerfish to name 3 favorites!

It is fun to chat with fishers and feel a sense of community with the people who are working hard to make sure that I don't go hungry. I also like the diversity of local products--going beyond salmon/tuna/shrimp. My hope is that local seafood is also more sustainable, fresher, better quality and supportive of the local economy and culture--although I recognize that that is not always the case.

The benefits of buying local seafood is that it is fresh, delicious, affordable, and supports North Carolina coastal communities. In addition, it often is sustainable (depending on the fishery) and shellfish farming, when done correctly, can improve water quality and provide much-needed habitat for marine organisms.
